## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Breaking Changes in the Original Code

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|-------|---------------|--------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works | Marked `[Obsolete]` in .NET 7+ |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` | Manual sync | Use `Channel<T>` instead |
| Signal race condition | Bug exists | Fixed by `Channel<T>` |

### Race Condition in the Original

```
Thread A: Enqueue(x) → Set()
Thread B: WaitOne() returns → Reset()  ← clears signal
Thread A: Enqueue(y) → Set()           ← happens before Reset()? signal lost!
Thread B: Dequeue() → processes x
           loops → WaitOne() → blocks forever (y stuck in queue)
```

The `Set()`/`Reset()` window also means `Dequeue()` can be called on an **empty queue** if two signals coalesce into one wake-up.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _processTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _processTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync yields items as they arrive and completes
        // when the writer is marked complete or the token is cancelled.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public bool Enqueue(string item)
    {
        // Returns false if the channel is completed (shutting down).
        return _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(bool drain = false)
    {
        // Stop accepting new items.
        _channel.Writer.TryComplete();

        if (drain)
        {
            // Let the loop finish remaining items, then exit naturally.
            // Apply a timeout so we don't wait forever.
            if (_processTask is not null)
            {
                using var timeout = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
                try { await _processTask.WaitAsync(timeout.Token); }
                catch (OperationCanceledException) { _cts.Cancel(); }
            }
        }
        else
        {
            // Cancel immediately — mirrors the original Abort() semantics.
            _cts.Cancel();
        }

        if (_processTask is not null)
        {
            try { await _processTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); }
            catch (TimeoutException) { /* forced shutdown exceeded — log and move on */ }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* expected */ }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### If You Need a Synchronous API

Use `BlockingCollection<T>` — the synchronous equivalent:

```csharp
public class EventProcessorSync : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            // GetConsumingEnumerable blocks until items arrive
            // and exits when CompleteAdding() is called + queue is drained.
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
                Handle(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* shutdown */ }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();   // signal "no more items"
        _cts.Cancel();            // interrupt immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);      // wait up to 5s — no Abort() needed
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls Summary

1. **`Thread.Abort()` is gone** — no replacement. Use cooperative cancellation (`CancellationToken`) instead. There is no way to forcibly kill a thread in .NET 8.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` is obsolete** — it only interrupts managed waits (`Thread.Sleep`, `WaitOne`), not arbitrary code. `CancellationToken` is strictly superior.

3. **`Channel<T>` eliminates the entire signal/lock/queue pattern** — no `ManualResetEvent`, no `lock`, no race conditions. One type, zero bugs.

4. **`Handle()` should check cancellation** — if `Handle()` is long-running, accept a `CancellationToken` and check it periodically. Without `Thread.Abort()`, a non-cooperative `Handle()` will block shutdown.

5. **`IsBackground = true`** — if using `Thread` directly, set this so the thread won't prevent process exit. The original code omits this.
